snippet.textDisplay:
I was never a big 40K fan, just know about it from the zeitgeist. But a friend told me I had to watch this.

And... holy fuck. This miniseries is literally perfect, as in, I can't think of any criticism at all.
It's short, but that almost helps it along; not a single second is wasted.

I've watched it five times and keep noticing new microscopic details every time.
Even setting aside the 40K baggage, this is just sci-fi action done RIGHT.


First bit of fiction I've ever seen or read that managed to drive into my skull the horrible meaning of the word 'supersoldier'. These marines are the heroes of the story, and they're exhilarating to watch, but at the same time they're deeply disturbing and I'm glad not to live in a universe where they exist.



Holy fuck, mate. You are the new patron god of CGI artists.

snippet.textDisplay:
My favourite thing about these is your direction in making the Space Marines actually behave and act like trained soldiers, let alone life long trained genetically optimised super soldiers. It's something I genuinely have never seen in any movie ever made; the audience is always made to relate to the stupidity, untrained and unskilled behaviour of the actors on screen. This though, this is satisfyingly authentic.

Another unique aspect of you as a director is how you use silence, especially abruptly to communicate. God damn you're just so good...

snippet.textDisplay:
A hypothesis on that final scene: the Space Marines were rescued by the Emperor's influence.


I base this mostly on the imagery of the final scene but we see the Astartes's connection to the orb severed right after they are absorbed and pulled into said orb. Next we see we are watching one of the Space Marines standing before a seemingly endless gallery of corpses. The scene is one of decayed stagnancy that combines with a kind of baroque majesty lit by a distant golden glow. This is very similar to illustrations of the Emperor in the current day, a decayed corpse sitting atop the Golden Throne surrounded by a stagnant and crumbling imperium.


The corpses shown appear to be long dead humans which leads me to suspect that these are the remains of the multitude of psykers sacrificed to keep the emperor going while he powers the Golden Throne.


Thoughts?

snippet.textDisplay:
I wish that Space Marines were this powerful in (the wargame) 40k. I enjoyed the height difference between marines and regular hoomins.
The crotch gap was not visible on the CGI marines. That is good.
The ammunition counters were a nice detail.
I nitpick that the Marines did not wear any webbing or ammunition harnesses. I take the initiative and model appropriate amounts of magazines and ammo on my miniatures. I still want to see Marines with proper loads of ammo.
